## Tabackstory

I’ve always fancied myself a bit of an inventor. When I was 2, my rattle broke, and by the next morning I had the auto-shaker 9000. It mysteriously fell out of my father’s trade ship, the Merry Weather, the very next week. (father: [[Walter Nackle]])

Wait, where are my manners? (probably off with that spanner I keep losing) My name is Tabber Nackle, and this is the start of my story. 

When I turned 5, it rained for three days straight. I wanted to go outside and play on the docks, but my mother (Ember) was afraid I’d catch a cold. I showed her! My rain zapper made short work of any raindrops silly enough to fall near me. It looked pretty cool sitting on my shoulder, too.

In the winter of my tenth year the Silverfrost thieves’ guild, the Silent Swipers, hit our shop. They took everything, even my mother’s silver lockbox where she kept our savings. I woke up to her sobbing. I was ready to swear my undying revenge, but my father stopped me. He couldn’t bear to see my innocence sullied. 

Instead we set off across the sea, trading this for that, and that for a bit more, and a bit more for gems. We traded the gems for spices, the spices for silk, and the silk for gold. Soon my family was once again wealthy, and we settled down in Aquanona. 

My father tried to teach me the merchant’s trade, but all the traveling had whet my thirst for adventure. Ledgers and inventories were never as interesting as the next big city. Trade routes became treasure maps. I’d frequently go with our family friend Big Magnus, who now captained the Merry Weather, on trading expeditions. 

Magnus was a half-orc whose first love was the sea. He was a skilled drinker, a skilled brawler, and a skilled intimidator. Woe befell many merchants who tried to swindle our crew, and worse came to the few pirates who thought us an easy mark.

I kept any books we found, reading them at night by the light of my super candle and trading them out whenever I got the chance. I read tales of fascinating adventures, learned seamanship and navigation and ten thousand different knots. But what fascinated me most was the artifacts. Scrawled in diaries and sung in legends, they told of mythical swords, enchanting shields, powerful bows, and impregnable armor.

When I got back to Aquanona after a particularly exciting trip, my father decided I would be happier reading even more books at the University of Waterblue. We said tearful goodbyes, I left my parents a parting gift, and I left to go to the university.

### Chapter 2

"You are hereby expelled, and you have until noon to get off of these grounds or be jailed for trespassing!"

Well damn. That didn't go quite how I had hoped. But really, it wasn't my fault! How was I supposed to know that the crystal fluid would explode when it was exposed to a current and the harmonic resonator? It wasn't like I wanted the dorms to collapse onto the mess hall. I just wanted to test out my new invention, the mood elevator, right before the social. 

Oh well. I guess I'll keep that book of legends from the library I've been reading. 

I've always loved inventing things, and sometimes it even goes well! That heat transducer has made my parents' shop the coolest place in town. Literally.

But I digress. I got into this prestigious university as much on my academic merits as my parents' money. I got 127% on the aptitude test! I've been studying hard for almost a year now, and my history and mathematics have drastically improved. I've also come up with a few new gadgets in that time, which is good now that I'm out on my heels. 

Ah well. I was just reading last night about the Shield of the Heralds. They say it weighs almost nothing, and that the bearer can't be touched by blade nor spell nor arrow. One legend even says there's armor to match, but I don't know how much of this book has trustworthy sources. I'll have to find more libraries and elders to peruse and prod for the information I need. And I know just where to start. 

### Chapter 3

Well, Autumnmoor seemed as good a place as any to look. The local lord, Jayson, has been very kind to me. He’s opened up his library and given me a bed and a room. I think I’ll stay here a while. People come here from everywhere, bringing news, trade, and more books. 

*** a few years later ***

Well, I’ve opened up a shop here in Autumnmoor. After I helped Arin Brimstone, the local blacksmith, automate her forge bellows, she offered me the building next door. It’s cozy, and her scrap metal has been excellent for building it into a shop befitting a gnome of my stature. I even put a working toy train on my sign: Tabber’s Mechanical Wizardry. 

I still want to be an adventurer, but an adventurer without money and friends is a dead adventurer. People come through all the time, I’m sure I can find a party to tag along with.

People and Places

Walter Alexandar Nackle: Tabber’s Father. Gnome. Quick witted and charming. Forgets everything not related to business, including birthdays. Shrewd businessman and trader. Average sailor.

Ember Nathalie Nackle (nee Ledger): Tabber’s Mother. Also Gnome. True to her maiden name, keeps a mean inventory. Neat freak. Hates sailing. Loves figurines.

(Big) Magnus Maxitaur: Half-Orc brawler. Magnus always loved the sea, and he got captured by slave traders when he tried to sneak onto a ship. Walter “bargained” with the traders while Ember set the slaves free, and Magnus took up sailing. Years later, he came back to Aquanona and Walter hired him as captain of the Merry Weather.

Arin Brimstone: Dwarf blacksmith of Autumnmoor. Makes gloves of chainmail so fine it feels like cloth. Surprisingly cool-tempered. World wise. 

The Merry Weather: The ship that belongs to the Nackle family. Constructed by Tabber’s grandfather and great grandfather, this ship is a caravel with triangular sails:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

[Aquanona](Locations/Aquanona): A large port city on the Northeastern border of Anterra. Known as the city of jewels due to a large nearby mine and surface level lapis lazuli. 

The University of Waterblue: A university located on a small island in the Fiery Isles. Produced some of the world’s finest wizards, who put permanent lights under the water surrounding the island so that ships could find it at night. The administration building is a fort that has stood for thousands of years.
